<h2>How To Get Started With Megam</h2>
<hr/>
<h3>Try Megam</h3>
<div class="span-9 append-1">
	<h4>Option 1: Free, Hosted Test Environment</h4>
	<p class="environments">
		To see how a live Megam cloud on cloud operates, you can play in the free sandbox by siging up an account 
		<%= link_to signup_path %>. TryStack is a cloud built and managed by the OpenStack community to make evaluating OpenStack painless, particularly if you're developing a cloud app or want to see what the Dashboard looks like from an admin or end user perspective.
	</p>	
</div>
<div class="span-9 last">
	<h4>Option 2: Private Hosted Environment</h4>
	<p class="environments">
		For  developers that want to actually get involved in writing the next  version of OpenStack, there is a great tool called <a href="http://devstack.org/">DevStack</a> where a  complete cloud can be installed and run from your laptop (or even inside  of a VM on a cloud). Note: this option is more suited to python developers who want to eventually contribute code.
	</p>
	<p>
		<a class="roundedButton" href="http://devstack.org/"><strong>Running DevStack</strong>: Quick Start</a>
	</p>
</div>
<div class="span-19 last">
	<div class="public-clouds">
		<p>
			<strong>Public Clouds:</strong> There are also OpenStack-powered public clouds in production across the world, including <a href="http://www.rackspace.com/">Rackspace</a>, <a href="http://www.enovance.com/">eNovance</a>, <a href="http://www.internap.com/">Internap</a> and <a href="https://www.hpcloud.com/">HP</a>, where you can see OpenStack in action.
		</p>
	</div>
</div>
